BugPattern.ShortDescription: Format string should use %n rather than \n
BugPattern.Details: This format string includes a newline character (\n). In format strings, it is generally preferable to use %n, which will produce the platform-specific line separator.

BugPattern.ShortDescription: Useless control flow to next line
BugPattern.Details:
This method contains a useless control flow statement in which control flow follows to the same or following line regardless of whether or not the branch is taken. Often, this is caused by inadvertently using an empty statement as the body of an if statement, e.g.:

if (argv.length == 1);
    System.out.println("Hello, " + argv[0]);

BugPattern.ShortDescription: Field should be both final and package protected
BugPattern.Details: A mutable static field could be changed by malicious code or by accident from another package. The field could be made package protected and/or made final to avoid this vulnerability.

BugPattern.ShortDescription: Possible null pointer dereference due to return value of called method
BugPattern.Details: The return value from a method is dereferenced without a null check, and the return value of that method is one that should generally be checked for null. This may lead to a NullPointerException when the code is executed.

BugPattern.ShortDescription: Switch statement found where default case is missing
BugPattern.Details:
This method contains a switch statement where default case is missing. Usually you need to provide a default case.

Because the analysis only looks at the generated bytecode, this warning can be incorrect triggered if the default case is at the end of the switch statement and the switch statement doesn't contain break statements for other cases.
A mutable static field could be changed by malicious code or by accident. The field could be made package protected to avoid this vulnerability.
